ğŸ”¹ What is Operator Overloading?
Imagine you have two toy cars. Normally, you can add numbers like 2 + 3 = 5, but can you add two toy cars? ğŸš—â•ğŸš—

ğŸ¤” C++ allows you to define what +, -, *, / mean for your own custom objects! This is called Operator Overloading.

ğŸ“Œ Think of it like this:

The + operator usually adds numbers (2 + 3 = 5).
But with operator overloading, you can make + combine two objects in any way you want!
ğŸ”¹ Example: Adding Two Complex Numbers
ğŸ“Œ Without Overloading

cpp
Copy
Edit
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Complex {
public:
    int real, imag;

    Complex(int r, int i) {
        real = r;
        imag = i;
    }
};

int main() {
    Complex c1(3, 4), c2(2, 5);
    
    // We can't use + directly! âŒ
    // Complex c3 = c1 + c2;  // ERROR âŒ

    return 0;
}
ğŸš€ C++ doesnâ€™t know how to add Complex numbers! We need operator overloading.

ğŸ”¹ Overloading the + Operator
ğŸ“Œ With Operator Overloading

cpp
Copy
Edit
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Complex {
public:
    int real, imag;

    Complex(int r, int i) {
        real = r;
        imag = i;
    }

    // Overloading the + operator
    Complex operator+(const Complex& obj) {
        Complex result(real + obj.real, imag + obj.imag);
        return result;
    }
};

int main() {
    Complex c1(3, 4), c2(2, 5);
    Complex c3 = c1 + c2;  // Now it works! ğŸ‰

    cout << "Result: " << c3.real << " + " << c3.imag << "i" << endl;
    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:

go
Copy
Edit
Result: 5 + 9i
ğŸš€ Now + works for Complex numbers because we defined it!

ğŸ”¹ How Does Operator Overloading Work?
ğŸ“Œ Syntax for Operator Overloading

cpp
Copy
Edit
returnType operatorOPERATOR(argument) {
    // Define custom behavior for the operator
}
operator+ â†’ Overloads +
operator- â†’ Overloads -
operator* â†’ Overloads *
operator/ â†’ Overloads /
ğŸ”¹ Overloading the - Operator
ğŸ“Œ Example: Subtracting Two Complex Numbers

cpp
Copy
Edit
class Complex {
public:
    int real, imag;

    Complex(int r, int i) {
        real = r;
        imag = i;
    }

    // Overloading the - operator
    Complex operator-(const Complex& obj) {
        Complex result(real - obj.real, imag - obj.imag);
        return result;
    }
};

int main() {
    Complex c1(7, 9), c2(3, 4);
    Complex c3 = c1 - c2;

    cout << "Result: " << c3.real << " + " << c3.imag << "i" << endl;
    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:

go
Copy
Edit
Result: 4 + 5i
ğŸš€ Now - works for Complex numbers!

ğŸ”¹ Overloading the * Operator
ğŸ“Œ Example: Multiplying Two Complex Numbers

cpp
Copy
Edit
class Complex {
public:
    int real, imag;

    Complex(int r, int i) {
        real = r;
        imag = i;
    }

    // Overloading the * operator
    Complex operator*(const Complex& obj) {
        Complex result((real * obj.real - imag * obj.imag),
                       (real * obj.imag + imag * obj.real));
        return result;
    }
};

int main() {
    Complex c1(1, 2), c2(3, 4);
    Complex c3 = c1 * c2;

    cout << "Result: " << c3.real << " + " << c3.imag << "i" << endl;
    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:

go
Copy
Edit
Result: -5 + 10i
ğŸš€ Now * works for Complex numbers!

ğŸ”¹ Overloading the << Operator for cout
ğŸ“Œ Printing Objects with <<

cpp
Copy
Edit
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Complex {
public:
    int real, imag;

    Complex(int r, int i) {
        real = r;
        imag = i;
    }

    // Overloading the << operator
    friend ostream& operator<<(ostream& out, const Complex& obj) {
        out << obj.real << " + " << obj.imag << "i";
        return out;
    }
};

int main() {
    Complex c1(3, 4);
    cout << "Complex Number: " << c1 << endl;
    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:

mathematica
Copy
Edit
Complex Number: 3 + 4i
ğŸš€ Now << works with cout for Complex numbers!

ğŸ”¹ Rules of Operator Overloading
âœ” Only existing operators can be overloaded.
âœ” At least one operand must be a user-defined class.
âœ” Overloaded operators keep their precedence.
âœ” Some operators (::, sizeof, .*, ?:) can't be overloaded.

ğŸ”¹ Summary
âœ” Operator Overloading lets you define how operators work for custom classes.
âœ” You can overload +, -, *, /, <<, and many more!
âœ” Use friend for overloading << and >>.
âœ” Objects behave like numbers when overloaded!

